  "prompt": "How do I calculate mass of the moon using mass of the earth?",
  "response": "To calculate the mass of the Moon using the mass of the Earth, you can use the orbital relationship between the two bodies. Here's a step-by-step method:\n\n1) Use Newton's law of universal gravitation and orbital mechanics:\n   - The gravitational force between Earth and Moon is: F = G(M1 * M2)/r\u00b2\n   - Where G is the gravitational constant, M1 is Earth's mass, M2 is Moon's mass, r is the distance between their centers\n\n2) Use orbital period information:\n   - Use the orbital period formula: T\u00b2 = (4\u03c0\u00b2r\u00b3)/(G(M1 + M2))\n\n3) Rearrange the equation to solve for Moon's mass:\n   - M2 = (4\u03c0\u00b2r\u00b3)/(G * T\u00b2) - M1\n\n4) You'll need these known values:\n   - Earth's mass: 5.97 \u00d7 10^24 kg\n   - Distance between Earth and Moon: ~384,400 km\n   - Orbital period: ~27.3 days\n\n5) Plug in the values and calculate\n\nThe result is approximately 7.34 \u00d7 10^22 kg, which is about 1.2% of Earth's mass.\n\nNote: Precise calculations require careful consideration of all variables.",
